We had to restructure many of our questions and the planned analysis to answer these questions.

Original questions:

Nic:

1) How significant are variables like intentional walks, sacrifice bunts, sacrifice flies, double plays, and caught stealing going to be in predicting a player’s salary? Will they get removed by a regularization model? 2) How accurate are your models in predicting players’ salaries based on mean squared error? 3) How accurate are your clustering models in grouping players by their skills or salary levels based on silhouette scores?

Obada:

4) Which variables contribute the most to deciding how long a player's contract will be? 5) Do Batters with higher salaries actually play that much better than Batters with lower salaries? How does a change in salary affect a player's performance? 6) Which 3 stats for a batter are the most effective at determining their salary?

New questions:

Nic:

1) How accurate is our model at predicting salaries? 2) What are the top 5 most significant variables in determining salaries? 3) How strongly related is each variable to salary? Are there any variables with strong relationships to each other?

Obada:

4) Do batters with higher salaries actually play that much better than batters with lower salaries? 5) Are there any players who are overpaid? How about underpaid? How can we tell? 6) How well does our model do with predicting the salary for unseen data?

Originally our plan was to make a lasso model to determine variables and then make another linear model off of the chosen variables, but we eventually realized that lasso produces a linear model so we instead created a linear model based off variables we thought were the best and based off of their correlation to salary. We also had to scratch questions 1,4,6 because they were very similar so we created the new question 3,5,6. Question 3 is where we chose our own variables to make a linear mode. In question 5 we analyzed results from question 1 to see if individual players were under/over paid and if we thought this was correct. In question 6 we applied our lasso model to a few players of our choice. We also used a Gaussian Mixtures model for question 4 instead of the K-Means model that we wanted to use originally.

Cleaning Data¶

Calculating basic statistics such as batting average, slugging %, on base %

In [553]:
salaries["avg"] = salaries["h"] / salaries["ab"]

single = salaries["h"] - (salaries["hr"] + salaries["double"] + salaries["triple"])

salaries["slg"] = (single + (salaries["double"]*2) + (salaries["triple"]*3) + salaries["hr"]*4 ) / salaries["ab"]

salaries["pa"] = salaries["ab"] + salaries["bb"] + salaries["ibb"] + salaries["hbp"] + salaries["sh"] + salaries["sf"]

salaries["obp"] = (salaries["h"] + salaries["bb"] + salaries["hbp"])/(salaries["pa"])

salaries["ops"] = salaries["obp"] + salaries["slg"]

salaries["hr_per_ab"] = (salaries["hr"])/(salaries["ab"])

salaries["k_percentage"] = (salaries["so"])/(salaries["pa"])
salaries["bb_percentage"] = (salaries["bb"])/(salaries["pa"])

salaries["salaryM"] = salaries["salary"]/1000000

dummies = pd.get_dummies(salaries["pos"])

salaries = pd.concat([salaries,dummies], axis = 1)

Lasso Model¶

First, I decided to use a lasso model to predict player salaries. A lasso model was chosen because it can zero out the variables that increase the error of the overall model to make the most accurate model with the lowest error, and it will then run a linear regression model using the chosen variables. I decided to do this to find the top 5 variables most important in predicting salary. I also used a 80/20 train/test split for model validation. What a train test split does is that it splits the data into training and testing data, the training is the bigger portion of the data and it is used to fit our initial model and then once the initial model is created it is applied to the unseen testing data to see how the model performs on unseen data.

Based on the results from the Lasso model, it is not very accurate in predicting salaries. This can be shown by the low R2 score of 0.40 (40%) and the high mean squared error and mean average error values. This model is also slightly overfit shown by the R2 being higher in the training model (0.436) than the testing model (0.40), so the training model did slightly better than the testing model. When a model is overfit, the model is fit very well to training data and performs well on this data, but when the model is applied to the unseen testing data it performs poorly because it's too well fit to the training data. This shows that the model is too complex, this can be solved through reducing variables. The mean absolute error in the testing model is 2.63 which means that on average the model's predictions were 2.63 million dollars off. The R2 score of 0.40 means that 40% of the variance in our predicted salaries can be explained by our predictor variables, essentially our model is onlt 40% accurate, we obviously want this number to be higher if we want the most accurate predictions.

Although the scores and error metrics are not very good for our lasso model, the true versus predicted plot is not too bad. The plot has a loose linear relationship shown by the upward trend, but the graph somewhat explains why our model has such high error. The model is mostly accurate in predicting salaries in the 0-5 million range shown by the points in this area being clumped together, but once the graph moves into larger salaries it's not as accurate and the model mostly underestimates people with high salaries. This could either be that the model is predicting that these high salary players are being overpaid based on their stats, or the model just isn't accurate and cannot predict high salary players.

What are the top 5 most significant variables in determining salaries?¶

The graph above shows the values of all coefficients for the lasso model. The lasso model finds variables that increase error on the model and turn their coefficients to zero. The coefficients values tell us which variables will have the biggest impact on our predicted salary based on the size of the coefficient. The 5 variables with the highest coefficient values are SF (sac flies, 0.94), SH (sac hits, -0.93), RBI (0.77), BB (walks, 0.74), & R (runs, 0.75). This came as a surprise as we did not expect sacrifice flies or sacrifice hits to have a high significance in determining salary, or even be kept by the lasso model. These 2 variables actually had the 2 highest coefficient values at 0.94 and -0.93. So the model is saying for every sac fly a player hits, their salary will increase by 0.93 million (930K), that simply makes no sence because sacrifice flies are not a statistic that people even look at when determining a player's value. Even weirder, some variables like HR, batting average, and doubles, which we hypothesized would have a large effect on salary, were zeroed out by the lasso model as it believes they increase the error of the model.

The top 5 variables that have the highest correlation to salary are RBI (0.582), Plate Appearances (0.543), Hits (0.533), Walks (0.533), & Runs (0.531). Surpisingly, the stat with the highest correlation to salary only had a correlation of 0.54, so none of these variables have a very strong relationship to salary, so this could be why our lasso model did not perform very well. These variables are expected to have high correlation because these are all statistics that are highly considered to evaluate a player when evaluating a player's skills when deciding a how much to pay them.

Multicollinearity occurs when 2 predictor variables have a strong relationship to eachother, this is an issue because all predictor variables must be independent and if they are not, the model will be more complex than it needs to be and increase error due to there being 2 variables that can prove the same thing. When inspecting if any of the variables have multicollinearity issues, we found some variable pairs that have high correlation, for example: PA vs AB (0.9972), PA vs H (0.9736), AB vs H (0.9779), Slg vs Ops (0.9642), & R vs H (0.9935). These high correlations occured for two reasons. In the case of PA v H and AB v H, a high value in one of these variables will create a high value for the other, for example if you have a lot of at bats you are more likely to have more hits. For the case of plate appearances vs at bats and SLG v OPS, these variables are highly correlated because they are created variables based off of variables in the original dataset, so when we run a correlation matrix, the original and new variables may have very high correlation due to the fact the new variable is calculated from the original stat. OPS is calculated by adding slugging percentage and on base percentage, so OPS contains SLG so the two variables will have a high correlation.

Linear Model Based on Correlation Matrix¶

I was not too happy about the variables that were chosen by the lasso model and the overall performance of the model, so I decided to pick out variables that I believed would be the best for predicting salary based on my knowledge of baseball and the results of the correlation table to see if this model will do better. For my new linear model I chose to include the variables: position, Walks, Games, Plate appearances, Avg, SLG, Obp, Ops, So, Hr, RBI, Hits, and Doubles. I decided to use these variables because they are all statistics highly considered when evaluating a player's skills when trying to determine their salary. I decided to not use at bats because of its high correlation to plate appearances and because plate appearances had the highest correlation to salary (0.54). We also decided to not use runs scored because of its high correlation to hits.

Clustering Models¶

Do batters with higher salaries actually play that much better than batters with lower salaries?¶

The yellow cluster helps answer our question because there are players in this cluster with very low salaries and very good stats. For example, the player with the highest batting average (around .340) is in the purple cluster and makes less than a million dollars, while there are players in the yellow cluster with batting averages in the low .200’s who make more than 20 million a year. There is a similar occurrence with the other major stats like home runs and rbi’s as well, players with higher totals and low salaries and players with lower totals and high salaries.

Overall, players with higher salaries do not clearly play better than those with low salaries because there are many outside factors that can impact salary. This shows that there are many highly performing players who are underpaid and players who are overpaid. For example, younger players don’t make as much and might have a breakout season which could lead to a big payday in the future, while there are older players who have had their payday and make a lot of money but do not play up to their salary because they are old or simply aren’t good and were overpaid. Other outside factors could include how good of an agent a player has, if the player is a popular name, or if a player signs with a rich team (the Yankees) who are willing to overpay to obtain this player.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion neither of my models were good at predicting salary and I can attribute this because salary is largely subjective. There are many stats a team can use to evaluate if a player is valuable or not and then offer them a salary based off of this value and the team’s situation, but there is no way 100% accurately predict players' salaries based on their stats. A player may make more money simply because of their popularity, if their agent is good, or the wealth of the team they are signing with. This is shown by the fact that the model never predicts someone to have a salary over 15 million, players obtain large contracts because of their skills but also how willing a team is to pay and bargain with you and your agent. This is where salary becomes subjective.

Looking deeper into the results from our models and our analysis of the models while our linear model is not good at predicting salary based on loss functions and r2, I drew some interesting conclusions from this model. Based on our answer for question 5, the model was somewhat successful at finding if a player is over or underpaid. All my loss functions measure how accurate our results are compared to the true salary, but when we analyzed the predictions and compared them to the player and used our knowledge of this player and their skill set, the model was correct some of the time. Use Matt Adams for example, he made 500K and the model predicted him to make 9 million. The model was correct that Adams was underpaid, but giving him a 9 million salary is a bit of a stretch. Looking at other good players with low salaries, the model performs similarly. The model does not do very well at predicting high salary players' salaries based on question 6 and the lasso true versus predicted plot. In the plot, the plots for lower salaries are much closer and once the graph moves into true salaries the points get more spread out. So while the model isn't the most accurate, it can at least somewhat evaluate if a player is over or underpaid.

I also think that the model could have been more accurate if there were some more advanced stats included in the model that put all players on the same scale and assign them a value based on all of their stats combined. An example of this is WAR (wins above replacement) and WRC+ (weighted runs created plus). I could not calculate these statistics based on our dataset though. These stats would possibly make the model more accurate because there are players with many different skill sets that have high salaries. There could be power hitters who hit a lot of homeruns and will have high rbi's, slg%, and ops, but might not have the highest batting average; or there could be contact hitters who have high batting averages and obp but have a low number of home runs and rbi's and have low slg% and ops. If we had stats to put all players on the same scale, the model might be better at predicting salaries for these different player skill sets.

Overall, salaries are not something a model can truly predict because of factors that are not connected to the player's stats and skills that may positively or negatively affect their salary.
